We can take a closer look at coverage across different simulation scenarios.

SER methods (both Laplace and ABF approximation) exhibit poor coverage in the most unbalanced case-control ratio. Coverage improves for both methods when the case-control ratio is less severe.

If we look at coverage as a function of signal strength (gamma = PVE by casual variant on liability), SER methods slightly undercover for weak effects and very strong effects. The mis-coverage of the ABF approximation is much worse than the Laplace approximation for the strongest signals.

ABF and RSS L = 1, expectedly give very similar PIPs, since the RSS likelihood for L=1 essentially uses ABFs (differences are due to differences in estimating prior variance hyper-parameter).

The Laplace ABF gives better ordering for the PIPs, that is a win!

# fdp vs power
fdp_plot <- res_pip %>%
    filter(name == 'ser') %>%
    unnest_longer(c(pip, causal)) %>%
    ggplot(aes(pip, causal, color=method)) +

We see good coverage for most methods except for RSS (L=5). Similar to the SER case, we can safely filter out the uninformative CSs. We see that as we filter out more CSs we keep good coverage, but obviously lose discoveries. Here linear SuSiE is really doing quite well– the CSs have good coverage, and we discover a few more effects using linear SuSiE compared to logistic SuSiE.

ABF SuSiE and RSS have poor coverage compared to the other methods.

cs_size_filter_table <- function(max_cs_size){
    res_cs %>%
        filter(name == 'main') %>%
        filter(cs_size < max_cs_size) %>%
        mutate(max_cs_size = max_cs_size) %>%
        group_by(method) %>%
        summarize(coverage = mean(covered), n_found = list(table(n_found)), mean_cs_size = mean(cs_size), max_cs_size = max_cs_size[1]) %>%
        unnest_wider(n_found)
}

cs_cutoffs <- c(200, 100, 50, 40, 20, 10, 5, 1)

a <- purrr::map_dfr(cs_cutoffs, cs_size_filter_table) %>%
    ggplot(aes(x = max_cs_size, y = coverage, color = method)) +
    geom_path() + ggtitle('Coverage') + geom_hline(yintercept = 0.95)

b <- purrr::map_dfr(cs_cutoffs, cs_size_filter_table) %>%
    ggplot(aes(x = max_cs_size, y = `1`, color = method)) +
    geom_path() + ggtitle('Number of discoveries')

cowplot::plot_grid(a, b)
